The data set for assignment 5 is in pajek form. Pajek is a long established academic network analysis tool.

You can use the read_graph function to read the pajek file. It contains both the node and edgelist in one file.

library(igraph)

g<- read_graph(file="./data/Pairs/WordPairs.txt",format="pajek")

g<- as.undirected(g)

g<-simplify(g)

You will need too visualise the word association network around each target word. If you don’t have too many nodes it will be possible. Below is an example from library called ggraph, which allows fairly decent plotting of igraph networks. It’s based on ggplot2 so many of the techniques you used in the Data Viz class can be applied. You still need to set the fig.width and fig.height parameters of the R chunk in the Rmd file to 10 (for example) to get a decent plot. However, you will need to experiment with the parameter values to find the value that works best for your plot.

Here is a basic example of using the Game of Thrones data we looked at in an earlier week.

# ```{r fig.width = 10, fig.height= 10}


library(igraph)
library(ggraph)

nodes <- read.csv("./data/got-s4-nodes.csv")

# rename the columns. igraph expects a node to have a name or numerical id
names(nodes) <- c("name", "label")

edges <- read.csv("./data/got-s4-edges.csv")

# rename the columns. igraph expects an edge list to have a to and from column
names(edges) <- c("to", "from", "weight", "season")

# get rid of "season"
edges <- edges[,c(1,2,3)]


# The GOT data needs to be scaled (from 0 to 1)
library("scales")
edges$weight<-rescale(edges$weight)

# create the graph object specifying the nodes and edges
g <- graph_from_data_frame(edges, directed=FALSE, vertices=nodes)

g<-delete.edges(g, which(E(g)$weight < 0.025)) # remove low weighted edges

g<- delete.vertices(g,which(degree(g)==0)) # remove nodes with degree zero

## see the gggraph documentation for more presentation options.
## It is based on ggplot so anything you've learned in dataviz can also be applied
ggraph(g, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link2(aes(edge_alpha = weight), edge_width=0.3, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size=degree(g)), color = "deepskyblue",  alpha=0.4, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), size = 1.75, repel = FALSE) + # repel =TRUE stops labels overlapping; but also  attaches a segment line between node and text, which may be visually confusing if it overlaps with graph edges and nodes
  scale_size_area(max_size=10) + # recall we used this function in the bubble plot tutorial in Data Viz
  theme_void()
